# Stripe Best Practices

This guide outlines the definitive best practices for integrating Stripe into our applications. Adhere to these rules to ensure secure, performant, and maintainable payment flows. Always target the latest Stripe API version (`2025-12-15.clover` as of this writing) and keep SDKs up-to-date.

## 1. Code Organization & Structure

### 1.1. Secure API Key Management

Never hardcode API keys. Store them securely in environment variables.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
const stripe = require('stripe')('sk_test_YOUR_SECRET_KEY');
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
// .env
// STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_YOUR_SECRET_KEY
const stripe = require('stripe')(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY);
```

### 1.2. Stripe Client Initialization

Initialize the Stripe client once per process or module. Avoid re-initializing on every request to prevent resource overhead.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD (Node.js example)
// lib/stripe-client.js
const stripe = require('stripe')(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY, {
  apiVersion: '2025-12-15',
});
module.exports = stripe;

// In your service/route handler:
const stripeClient = require('../lib/stripe-client');
// ... use stripeClient for all API calls
```

## 2. Common Patterns & Anti-patterns

### 2.1. Modern Checkout Flows

Always use Stripe Checkout Sessions or Payment Intents with Stripe Elements for UI. These handle complex authentication, multi-currency, and compliance automatically, significantly reducing your PCI scope.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD: Building custom card input fields and handling raw card data directly
// Avoid handling raw card data on your server
const charge = await stripe.charges.create({ /* ... */ });
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD: Use Checkout Sessions for hosted pages
const session = await stripe.checkout.sessions.create({
  line_items: [{ price: 'price_123', quantity: 1 }],
  mode: 'payment',
  success_url: 'https://example.com/success',
  cancel_url: 'https://example.com/cancel',
});
// Redirect user to session.url
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD: Use Payment Intents + Elements for custom UI
const paymentIntent = await stripe.paymentIntents.create({
  amount: 1000,
  currency: 'usd',
  automatic_payment_methods: { enabled: true },
});
// Send paymentIntent.client_secret to frontend to use with Stripe Elements
```

### 2.2. Idempotency for Write Operations

Always include a unique `Idempotency-Key` header for all write requests (for example: creating payment intents, customers, refunds). This prevents duplicate operations during network retries.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
await stripe.paymentIntents.create({ amount: 1000, currency: 'usd' });
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD: Generate a stable, unique key per request
const { v4: uuidv4 } = require('uuid');
await stripe.paymentIntents.create(
  { amount: 1000, currency: 'usd' },
  { idempotencyKey: uuidv4() },
);
```

### 2.3. Metadata for Traceability

Attach relevant metadata to Stripe objects for easier debugging, reconciliation, and integration with internal business logic.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
await stripe.paymentIntents.create({
  amount: 2000,
  currency: 'usd',
  metadata: {
    order_id: 'ORDER-XYZ-123',
    user_id: 'user_abc',
    product_sku: 'PROD-001',
  },
});
```

### 2.4. API Versioning

Pin your API version in Stripe client initialization and for webhook endpoints. Regularly upgrade to benefit from new features and security patches, testing thoroughly.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD: Relying on Stripe default API version
const stripe = require('stripe')(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY);
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD: Explicitly set apiVersion
const stripe = require('stripe')(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY, {
  apiVersion: '2025-12-15',
});
// Ensure webhook endpoints also use this version in Dashboard
```

## 3. Error Handling

### 3.1. Catch Specific Stripe Errors

Handle Stripe error subclasses to provide precise feedback and implement appropriate retry logic. Always log the request ID.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
try {
  await stripe.paymentIntents.confirm(paymentIntentId);
} catch (error) {
  if (error.type === 'StripeCardError') {
    console.error(`Card declined: ${error.message} (Code: ${error.code}, Req ID: ${error.requestId})`);
  } else if (error.type === 'StripeInvalidRequestError') {
    console.error(`Invalid request: ${error.message} (Param: ${error.param}, Req ID: ${error.requestId})`);
  } else {
    console.error(`Generic Stripe error: ${error.message} (Req ID: ${error.requestId})`);
  }
}
```

### 3.2. Webhook-Driven Error Handling

For asynchronous outcomes (for example, delayed failures), rely on webhooks. Your server must be the source of truth for payment status.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
app.post('/webhook', async (req, res) => {
  // Verify Stripe signature before trusting payload
  const signature = req.headers['stripe-signature'];
  let event;
  try {
    event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(req.rawBody, signature, process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`Webhook signature verification failed: ${error.message}`);
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid signature');
  }
  if (event.type === 'payment_intent.payment_failed') {
    const paymentIntent = event.data.object;
    console.error(`Payment Intent ${paymentIntent.id} failed: ${paymentIntent.last_payment_error?.message}`);
    // Update order state in DB and notify customer
  }
  return res.status(200).send('ok');
});
```

## 4. Security & Compliance Essentials

### 4.1. Verify Webhook Signatures

Always verify webhook signatures using the endpoint secret. Never trust raw webhook payloads without verification.

### 4.2. Keep Secrets Server-Side

Never expose `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` to client-side code. Client code should only receive publishable keys and short-lived client secrets.

### 4.3. Minimize PCI Scope

Use Stripe-hosted or Stripe Elements-based flows. Do not store, process, or transmit raw card data through your servers.

## 5. Operational Excellence

### 5.1. Log Correlation Data

Log Stripe `requestId`, payment intent IDs, and internal order IDs together to simplify incident response and support.

### 5.2. Retry Strategy

Retry only transient failures with backoff, and always combine retries with idempotency keys.

### 5.3. Keep SDKs Updated

Update Stripe SDKs regularly and test API version upgrades in staging before production rollout.
